## Planning Security Defaults

Security defaults provide preconfigured security settings which can:

 - Require all users to register for multifactor authentication
 - Requiring all admins to perform MFA
 - Blocking legacy authenication protocols
 - Requring users to perform MFA when needed. 
 - Protecthing privileged activites like access to Azure portal.

 # Who should use security defaults:

 - Organizations that want to increase their security posture vut do not know or where to start

 - Organizations utilizing the free tier of Entra ID

 # Who should not use security defaults

 - Organizations currently using Conditional Access policies to bring signals together, make decisions, and enforce organizational policies. 

 - Organizations with Entra ID premium liceneses

 - Organizations with complex security requirements that warrent using Conditional Access

 # Unified multifactor authenication registration

 - All users must sign up for MFA and have 14 days to do so. After 14 days, they will be required to sign up to sign in.

 # Admin accounts requiured to sign in with MFA

 After registration with Multifactor Authentication is finished, the following nine Microsoft Entra administrator roles will be required to perform additional authentication every time they sign in:

- Global Administrator
- SharePoint Administrator
- Exchange Administrator
- Conditional Access Administrator
- Security Administrator
- Helpdesk Administrator
- Billing Administrator
- User Administrator
- Authentication Administrator